Horizontal Positional Accuracy Report:

When weighting compass and tape traverses for least squares adjustment, =
the default error variance assumed (by Walls) for each horizontal =
component is <total traverse length in feet>/100 ft=B2, which is =
equivalent to a standard deviation of 0.3 m for a 30-meter vector =
measurement. This being only a rough approximation of variance, the =
component errors are currently treated as if they were statistically =
similar and uncorrelated. Under these assumptions the expected =
horizontal unit variance estimate (UVE) resulting from an adjustment is =
1.0. Cave surveys, however, are significantly affected not only by =
random errors in clinometer and tape readings, but also by station =
positioning errors and systematic errors due to imperfect instrument =
calibration (among other things). Cave difficulty and skill of surveyors =
are important factors. When there are sufficient surveyed loops, the =
effects of these errors normally result in UVEs ranging from 1.0 to 2.0 =
in surveys believed to be of good quality. (CRF surveying methods and =
standards are assumed.)

The accuracy of a station's estimated UTM coordinates will depend on its =
distance from well-established benchmarks and how much control is =
provided by surveyed loops. Approximate confidence intervals can be =
computed from statistics derived from the least squares adjustment and =
error analysis. The required statistics are provided in the following =
numeric fields of the station shapefile:

SD_H      - A priori standard deviation of each horizontal component's =
error in meters.
SDUW_H    - A posteriori standard deviation of unit weight for each =
horizontal component.
LOOPS_H   - Loop count (degrees of freedom) for each horizontal =
component.

(Note that the standard deviation of unit weight is the square root of =
the UVE.) These numbers can be used to derive any of several popular =
kinds of approximate confidence intervals. For example, an a priori =
bound on either the Easting or Northing of a UTM position, at 90% =
confidence, would be computed as plus or minus 1.64 x SD_H. The radius =
of an approximate 90% confidence region would be 2.15 x SD_H. These =
intervals depend only on network geometry and the default variances used =
for weighting measurements. To obtain the corresponding a posteriori =
confidence interval, which depends on observed consistency (loop =
closures), we would replace SD_H with with SDUW_H x SD_H. This will be a =
legitimate confidence interval only if the loop count is large enough, =
say over 20 (generally the case for CRF data submissions to MCNP). For =
fewer loops, the radius of a confidence region can be computed using =
critical values of the F distribution, with 2 and 2 x LOOPS_H degrees of =
freedom. If there are no loops, only a priori bounds are possible.

