Vertical Positional Accuracy Report:

When weighting compass and tape traverses for least squares adjustment, =
the default error variance assumed (by Walls) for the measured vertical =
component is <total traverse length in feet>/100 ft=B2, which is =
equivalent to a standard deviation of 0.3 m for a 30-meter vector =
measurement. Under this assumption the expected vertical unit variance =
estimate (UVE) resulting from an adjustment is 1.0. Cave surveys, =
however, are significantly affected not only by random errors in =
instrument and tape readings, but also by station positioning errors and =
systematic errors due to imperfect instrument calibration (among other =
things). Cave difficulty and skill of surveyors are important factors. =
When there are sufficient surveyed loops, the effects of these errors =
normally result in UVEs ranging from 1.0 to 2.0 in surveys believed to =
be of good quality. (CRF surveying methods and standards are assumed.)

The accuracy of a station's estimated elivation will depend on its =
distance from well-established benchmarks and how much control is =
provided by surveyed loops. Approximate confidence intervals can be =
computed from statistics derived from the least squares adjustment and =
error analysis. The required statistics are provided in the following =
numeric fields of the station shapefile:

SD_V      - A priori standard deviation of the vertical component's =
error in meters.
SDUW_V    - A posteriori standard deviation of unit weight for the =
survey's vertical component.
LOOPS_V   - Loop count (degrees of freedom) for the survey's vertical =
component.

(Note that the standard deviation of unit weight is the square root of =
the UVE.) These numbers can be used to derive any of several popular =
kinds of approximate confidence intervals for an established elevation. =
For example, an a priori 90% confidence interval would be computed as =
plus or minus 1.64 x SD_V. This interval depends only on network =
geometry and the default variances used for weighting measurements. To =
obtain the corresponding a posteriori confidence interval, which depends =
on observed consistency (loop closures), we would replace SD_V with with =
SDUW_V x SD_V. This will be a legitimate confidence interval only if the =
loop count is large enough, say over 40 (generally the case for CRF data =
submissions to MCNP). For fewer loops, the confidence interval can be =
computed using critical values of the T distribution with LOOPS_V =
degrees of freedom. If there are no loops, only a priori bounds are =
possible.

